Accessibility Preferences (Ctrl + Alt + A)
English (USA)
This profile enables All in One Accessibility screen-reader. By using a screen reader, information from the device is announced in clear speech allowing a blind user to access devices on an equal footing with sighted counterparts.
This profile enables motor-impaired persons to operate the website using the keyboard. Users can also use shortcuts to jump to specific elements.
This profile adjusts the website so that it is accessible to the majority of visual impairments such as Degrading Eyesight, Tunnel Vision, Cataracts, Glaucoma, and others.
This profile adjusts website colors to suit individuals with the most prevalent forms of color blindness. Specific color blindness adjustments can be found within the 'color-blindness' settings.
This profile changes the font style, size, and spacing in order to make it easier for people with dyslexia to read the website content.
This profile provides various assistive features to help users with cognitive disabilities, such as Autism, Dyslexia, CVA, and others, to focus on the essential elements more easily.
This profile enables people with epilepsy to safely use the website by eliminating the risk of seizures resulting from flashing or blinking animations and risky color combinations.
This profile significantly reduces distractions and noise to help people with ADHD and Neurodivergent people browse, read, and focus on the essential elements more easily.

Advanced Code Breaking

Now we are getting into the more complex side of code breaking.

Be prepared for things to get turned upside down, backwards, and absolutely scrambled.

Evil Corp will do anything to keep us out of their way, but once you get a handle on this, we will be able to foil them yet again.

So, ears and eyes open for this last lesson because its your last chance ot make sure you've got everything before we assign you your first mission.

This isn't gonna be easy, Agent, but don't be intimidated. I know you'll do just fine as long as you keep at it.

Small Title

MISSION DEBRIEF

Last time, we discussed how decryption using Caesar Ciphers can work so long as you can figure out how much the letters of the alphabet are shifted. But how can you guess a shift?

One way for simple code is the pass and fail method of going through the alphabet to see if it spells a word out.

Lomaxk sk uaz!

 

If L is shifted by 9 to an O, then that makes Lomaxk into Orpdan, which isn't a word. Nope, isn't by 9 then.

This method could take a lot of time, but there are some short cuts that can make it easier, including using the rules of language!

 

Whatever language the cipher is written in has to follow certain rules. For example: In English, E is the most commonly used letter i nthe alphabet. If you see a lot of one letter, it's probably an E.

Lomaxk sk uaz!

 

If E is the most common letter, then I see two Ks in this sentence. What if K=E? That is shifted by 6 letters!

Exactly, Agent Q. If you try the phrase with shift 6, you get the English phrase. Good work!

Lomaxk sk uaz!

 

Now becomes

Figure me out!

 

Let's turn it up a notch

 

What happens in the cases when E isn't the most common letter in a sentence? Or what if there isn't an E at all?

U omz'f gzpqdefmzp, ngf U'xx fdk mzkimk.

Language tricks can still help us out. For instance, consider these three other English common rules:
 

  • A single letter is most likely an I or an A, since that's most common in English.

  • Apostrophes most often have a T like "can't" or the s like "Aqent Q's".  If there's two either a word that ends like "you'll" or "should've"

  •  After commas, the most common words are "and" and "but"

U omz'f gzpqdefmzp, ngf U'xx fdk mzkimk.

Oh! Those help. If two letters after the apostrophe is the same, then it most likely end in two "L"s.

Exactly. Other ways you could tackle this phrase is to take those rules and compare them to other ones.

For instance, Agent Q is right that the two letter Xs could be L, but what about that U in the front? That could be an A or and I. Why don't we try it comparing them?

If u is A then U'xx is A'll
or
if u is I then u'xx is I'll

 

Great! Between "A'll" and "I'll", only "I'll" is an actual word. Now, we figured out the shift and see if it words with the rest of the phrase.

Counting how far away L is from X (or I is from U), that means that it's 12 letters away from each other, and thus shift 12.

Let's try it!

Don't forget that you can write things down to make it easier! 

U omz'f gzpqdefmzp, ngf U'xx fdk mzkimk.

Now becomes

I can't understand, but I'll try anyway.

At least you now understand it. Why don't we try something even harder?

Oh yeah? We can handle it!

Time to level up

 

You remember how we said it could get tricker?

That's right. Codes can be double encrypted, or be written with secret words or scrambled and *then* put in a cipher. Whole sentences, to single words, to even letters can have their own shifts!

Oh no! There must be something we can do. Evil Corp can't win!

Fortunately, Agent P Quackers, we have some tricks we can use.

After all, as you learned earlier, the entire point of making a code is so that is can be decrypted by the person you want to receive the message. The means if you can get enough clues to understand how it works, you'll be able to break as long as you keep at it.

Oh yeah! That makes me much more confident to take them on!

Good to hear you are ready, Agent Q. The Boss will be stopping by any minute now to give you an assignment to prove you are ready to go on your first mission. If you need any help, don't be afraid to look back at the debrief for help.

Oh! Here he comes. Dust off your uniform, and look sharp, Agent!

Welcome, Agent. We have received messages from Evil corp and need your help decoding them. Agent X will be contacting you soon, so you and agent P be prepared and Report your results soon as possible.

  good luck. 

You hear that Agent? Let's get to work, and put all that earlier training we did to good use!

Remember Agent, Evil Corp has been using Caesar Ciphers to encrypt their messages. Its your job to reverse this and report what they have to say.

Incoming!

Agent X reporting:

We have received a message from that despicable Evil Corp. Looks like he's here to gloat. Big mistake! Read it, and see if you can get any good information out of him.

Agent X out.

 

 ."ibofsvon vksmozc" ord byp ppy zybn ord cgyxu xyyQ dkrd gyxu yn S del ,gyxu d'xyn S ?ucon qxsdsbg k rdsg xofkb k ccybm eyi xorg doq eyi yn dkrG

 

Holy Squeakers, Agent X doesn't kid around. This is the longest one so far!

Not to worry, Agent Q, we will be working as a team for this one. Naturally, you'll have an idea how to do approach this if it was smaller; look for clues!

Plus, one extra bonus is in Agent X's notes, it suggests the sentences might just be backwards!

 ."ibofsvon vksmozc" ord byp ppy zybn ord cgyxu xyyQ dkrd gyxu yn S del ,gyxu d'xyn S ?ucon qxsdsbg k rdsg xofkb k ccybm eyi xorg doq eyi yn dkrG

 

Looking at the punctuation to understand placement is called syntax. This process confirms Agent's X's idea that the code is likely reversed. If we get the letters and flip them, and they become a word, we cracked the code!

 ."ibofsvon vksmozc" ord byp ppy zybn ord cgyxu xyyQ dkrd gyxu yn S del ,gyxu d'xyn S ?ucon qxsdsbg k rdsg xofkb k ccybm eyi xorg doq eyi yn dkrG

 

I went ahead and marked all the places where clues commonly hide.

While we could count the most common letters to find the E, the parts that Agent Q have circled are likely to be all we need to know since we have access to the puncutation.

Assuming that Agent Q is correct, that would mean that the most important words or letters are S, K, DEL, D'XYN

S and K could be either and I or an A
 

DEL, since it's after a comma can be a "but" or an "and"

The D can either be a T or an S

Hold on! D is in both DEL and D'XYN. Since we know they are flipped that means that DEL and D'XYN are LED and NYX'D, so the only letter that is the same is the T in "but"

Very smart, Agent Q. One of the best things that you can do is compare similar parts of the rules. If you know a letter is going to be the same in two places, it's easier to test. Let's go ahead and see if that's right.

To test the theory, we can use T and D to count the number of shifts. That means you can repeat the alphabet and count how many letters are between T and D. Naturally you will pass Z while counting, so just start over at A until you reach D.

If you counted correctly, that would mean that T= D is 10 letters apart, and thus shift 10.

 ."yreviled laiceps" eht rof ffo pord eht swonk nooG taht wonk od I tub ,wonk t'nod I ?ksed gnitirw a htiw nevar a ssorc uoy nehw teg uoy od tahW

 

That's alright. Mistakes happen. Just make sure to double check your work just in case you missed a step somewhere.

Uh, that still doesn't look like anything English. Oh right, I forgot to flip it! 

What do you get when you cross a raven with a writing desk? I don't know, but I do know that Goon knows the drop off for the "special delivery". 

 

Nice work. Now we know that the Goon is up to something. Everything seems in order for your first Mission. You may either continue with the challenge below and help Agent Q, or Skip to the final debrief

I can't wait to work with you! But I gotta get that goon first. Meet you at the end.
